# LLM-as-tool REST integration (Saga 19).
#
# Calls a hosted LLM (via a local Ollama server) as a
# composable language-level builtin -- no longer just
# the REPL's :ask slash command. The reply is an MLPL
# string and feeds straight into the rest of the
# language: tokenize_bytes, experiment {}, etc.
#
# Requires a running Ollama server at
# http://localhost:11434 with `llama3.2` pulled.
# Skip this demo on CI / no-network envs -- it makes
# a real network call and depends on a local model.
#
# CLI-only. The browser cannot reach localhost Ollama
# without CORS allow-listing + a server-side proxy;
# Saga 21 ships `mlpl-serve` for that path. See
# docs/using-llm-tool.md.
#
# Run with:
#   mlpl-repl -f demos/llm_tool.mlpl

# ---- Tour 1: a single LLM call ----

reply = llm_call("http://localhost:11434", "Summarize MLPL in one sentence.", "llama3.2")
reply

# Whatever the local model returns. Typical shape:
#   "MLPL is a Rust-first array programming language
#    inspired by APL and J, designed for machine
#    learning experiments."

# ---- Tour 2: compose the reply into the rest of MLPL ----

# `tokenize_bytes` converts the reply string into a
# rank-1 array of byte tokens (vocab=256). Useful for
# quick token-count sanity checks or piping into a BPE
# tokenizer / embed lookup downstream.

reply_tokens = tokenize_bytes(reply)
reply_tokens

# Output is a [N] f64 array where N is the byte count
# of the reply; values are the byte values 0..256.

# ---- Expected output format ----

# `reply` prints as a string scalar (no shape header).
# `reply_tokens` prints as a rank-1 array; on a typical
# llama3.2 reply this will be ~100-300 bytes long.

# ---- Non-goals (deferred) ----

# Streaming SSE, OpenAI-style tool calling, multi-turn
# chat threading, request batching, in-source auth
# secrets, and web/WASM support all stay deferred.
# See contracts/eval-contract/llm-call.md and
# docs/using-llm-tool.md for the full list.
